review_blob: Had at brewery. This was a fine beer except there was zero smoky character. Maybe Im mistaken, but that makes it entirely unlike any schwarzbier Ive had before. But it was a reasonable (if boring) beer so a 3.1 seems fair.
Light golden. A bit watery. Light Belgian. Flavor best part. Pretty happy with this.

Had at brewery. White head. Served cold. Super boozy and chocolate nose. Body super creamy. Like a lacto stout almost. Flavor is very sweet and alcoholic. Barrel character is more obvious in the aroma. Subtle in flavor. This is as promised.

So good I had to rate it. Unexceptional amber color, clear, with minimal white head. Aroma is actually somewhat muted, some citrus in there. But I love the flavor. Quite balanced, seems to have this sweet kick on the back end. Fruity, to be sure. Refreshing... Maybe I just really wanted a beer just now.

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob: Felt like I had to rate this due to my love for space and, in particular, the Sagan quote this beers name references. Got it at the brewery to go. Almost plays like a regular IPA but ultimately nothing too special. Didnt explode all over me like previous HotDs (its been a few years since my last, perhaps their technique has changed). Still opaque from the bottle conditioning which is nice since I dont see that as much anymore. Somewhat lemony and refreshing aroma. Solid body. A little thin on the flavor for a DIPA I was suprised to see that was the style. Your usual west coast hop flavor dominates, not too bitter though. I like a little more fruit/dimension in my DIPA.
beer_name: Hair of the Dog Blue Dot Double IPA

review_blob: Pitch black. Pretty golden bubbles up top. A little cold to be smelling it, ill come back to that. But its a bit chalky and chocolatey. Flavor is straightforward smoked malts. Quite balanced flavor profile, front to back. Alcohol well hidden. a bit creamy like a lactose stout. Hint of cooked vegetables.... Thats a new flavor suggestion from the site. A lot better than stuff like Edmund Fitz to my preference. A bit on the thin side for what otherwise seems like an impy. not really fair to call it a stout probably. Good show.

toffee colored. big fluffy head. barnyard aroma, not much hops for an IPA. fairly thin. kinda like a weak amber ale. in fact, probably more malt than hops. still seems fairly light/sessionable. completely unoffensive.

stillwater barrel debauched - mild amber clean appearance with nice thin bubbled head. clear, no bubbles. didnt there used to be a word to describe the bubbles? in any case. smells like a gueze , pretty vinaigery without much else going on. i dont get how people get complexity out of this. its just sour smelling. i guess im getting cantankerous. it tastes pretty great. it tastes sour. pretty good malt backing it making it not overly puckeringly sour. very poor english in this review. id say im very happy with tihs.
beer_name: Stillwater Import Series Vol. 5 Debauched - Brunello Barrel

review_blob:
stillwater existent. by recommendation. little head dissipates quitckly. dirty brown earthy color, opaque. pretty muted smell at this temperature, a bit musty,
 somewhat bland flavor. not really a traditional farmhouse or saison by any means. sort of reminds me of a bland abbey dubbel. not really much hops either. mostly watery with a little bit of bitterness on the back end. i just realized this pretty much reminds of a brown ale, which explains why i find it inordinately boring.

Draft at Swift in NYC. This is a joke. There was hardly any IPA character at all. It was all Belgian white with a trace of hops in the flavor. Overwhelming wheat and orange aroma, super effervescent body with, again, all wheat flavor. Fairly easy to drink, Id give this to a girl on a first date.

beer_brewer_name: Hair of the Dog Brewing Company
review_blob: purchased in nyc. golden brown color with mild opacity. minimal head. pretty stinky aroma with trace floral hops. almost a belgo-pale ale. flavor makes it seem not totally fresh, though i guess pilsener hops could explain that as well as part of the aroma. its super light in body and totally drinkable. not much fruity/floral hops. mild bitterness and rather sweet. quite interesting overall, though not sure what id call it.

i cant believe ive never rated this. i know i havent had it in like five years. but perhaps ive never had it at all. i thought i remembered it being super chalky, but its nothing like that. its a totally pleasant surprise. looks kinda watery with really no head at all.  a ton of dregs, which is a welcome surprise given most beers are filtered nowadays. aroma, like the taste, has caramel all over the place. i think the only other time ive had something like that was probably the southern tier creme brulee. some coffee. whats up tyler

looks like anchor porter. please refer to that rating to see what i had to say about. moderate chocolate, not much coffee. decent malt backbone, roasted malt etc. fairly light mouthfeel, closer to what i expect from a porter. i could drink a bunch of these pretty easily.

By virtue of the 4 I gave the oakshire watershed IPA  for appearance, i am forced to give this beer the same rating as it looks exactly the same. please refer to my rating of the former to see what i thought of the appearance. aroma: caramel, toast, resin, earthy. taste: heavy sweet, medium bitter, light sour, light salty, no umami. i think the ratebeer taste suggestions could be a little more varied. im too far removed from rating to be able to identify flavors, not that i ever really was able to in the first place. body is the same as the last beer.

Fairly standard golden amber appearance with limited head, no opacity. aroma is fairly muted and leans towards malt i would say, relative to most IPA / pacific NW IPas. the taste is difficult to describe. not too much alcohol. fantastic! i like that its pretty thin
An excellent take. Poured at the brewpub. White head, orange tan and opaque body. Smells good. Tastes good.  Balance supreme.
UPDATED: JUL 1, 2011

was pretty impressed with this guy. was at a festival tonight and ordered a big of it (12oz). actually unlike any belgian ipa ive had before. the two components (belgian and ipa) were both really understated and well melded. so instead of it being a beer with both yelling at you trying to get your attention, like most belgian ipas, it was just a balanced, drinkity beer
beer_name: Goose Island Batch 4000 Belgian Imperial IPA

review_blob: Im back, f*ckers. This was the first new beer ive seen on draft in a while. Probably the best cherry beer Ive had, not including New Glarus because the belgian red and enigma are incomparable. This one was super subtle and crafted the cherry into the beer really well, which is generally uncommon in fruit beers. This is to cherry beers what the southern tier pumpkin beer is to pumpkin beers

thanks cmubeerman.  for my 1000 rating i guess ill be the first to rate this awful mead.  pours lighter than busch lite though the same color and obviously with no head.  it smells pretty bad (and ive loved every other mead ive ever had).  honestly it smells like a pretty foul, days old, cheap white wine.  a bit of vanilla under it.  taste is, mercifully, more in line with meads ive had.  full bodied sweetness, definitely some off flavors all over it, but if you remove them its reasonably tasty.  incredibly alcoholic all over for 12%. the jagdiva and sweet blossom were billion times better.

thanks cmubeerman. hardly any head. pretty watery consistency, plum red color, pretty. SOY BOMB aroma. fair amount of barrel, lots of nuts. a bit of toothpaste upon suggestion. alcohol is pretty well hidden. pretty dark fruity, but not really thick. a bit spicy too. tast is a little thin, maybe even. the dregs were actually the best pour in the bottle.

pours hazy brown peach.  tiny head. smells like a tripel, but with some hops enough to make me think of the de ranke XX.  the saaz actually really hurts it, such that the aroma is totally unappetizing and mess. slightly thin, but that might be what they were going for. im not sure what style this is supposed to be. pretty yucky. meh, not awful for a session beer perhaps.

cask at the MBAfest.  so it pours a hazy deep brown with very little head.  smells pretty hoppy and dishwasher soapy for an ESB.  pretty damned tasty.  one of the best beers ive had in a while. starts out a thick chewy caramel malt, which gives way to a nice pecan roof.  a noteworthy bitter hop finish.  great profile.  really takes beautifully to the cask.  best new thing ive had from goose island since the black cat 2 years ago.
UPDATED: MAY 16, 2009
beer_name: Tyranena BGW Paradise by the Dashboard Lights

review_blob: clear, surprisingly light. cherry brown. no head. liquid hard candy. very sweet, nutty. better than those awful ones i had here last time (la trappe, though ironically enough i gave that dubbel a higher overall score)

bottle. seems like this should have more alcohol with a name like ambergeddon.  well, whatever.  pours an uninspired, uniform straight red color. smells pretty damned good, actually, especially from afar, where fruit candy dominates. closer, its much hoppier and not unlike a 2 hearted.  Flavor is a bit of a letdown, with not much hop character, pretty dry, and some metal.  Just kinda mild/boring, nothing particularly bad about it.  Overall, another good offering from ale asylum (2 for 2).  And much better than i was expecting it to be.
thanks cmubeerman.  bottle. pours pitch black, some head that lasts. smell is roasty, i guess a little chocolate, and pretty chalky. flavor is chalky, hardly chocolate, and gives me heartburn.  meh.
beer_name: Sand Creek Oscars Chocolate Oatmeal Stout

review_blob:
thanks cmubeerman. pours admirable cherry brown with boastful 1/2 foamy head.  pretty hoppy in that i could smell them far away while pouring. pretty floral. slightly flat, pretty malty. served cask temp
good balance, not bad.

thanks cmubeerman. bottle. chocolate copper color, clear. lasting head. smells like an avery barleywine or some other avery thing: beer, alcohol, nuts. a little hoppy, actually. not great. super alcoholic without much flavor. not good. ok.
beer_name: New Glarus Unplugged Iced Barley Wine

review_blob: very thin black pour. pretty roasty aroma, a bit plasticy. flavor is somewhat chocolatey, definitely plasticy.  guess roasty. really nothing special at all.

bottle from publican (which blows ass). i was rather disappointed with this pos at $15. i only got it since i was at this dinner with 10 friends for one of theirs birthday, and i knew that we were all gonna split the check, and as a vegetarian i knew id get royally screwed fiscally (and they were going crazy with ordering communal meat dishes), so i just ordered overly expensive beers to compensate.  this was red and hazy, smelled of a bit of malt but mostly metal and alcohol, tasted like rotten fruit, alcohol, and rose, and was a tremendous waste of money.

had this lousy beer at the publican (which also sucks balls).  so it poured pretty dark brown but still letting light pass through. lots of head. tasted pretty nutty, but not really in a good way.  pretty much just a throwaway beer, i know i certainly was just getting through it.

thanks nhorween. this was pretty good. not too artificial cherry, but clearly in the fruit beer style. very light and effervescent. definitely pink and bubbly. still held character as a beer. drinkable.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: thanks oberdorf. Hazy yellow orange. Super malt honey aroma, a litle funk, great subtle hop profile. Pretty sundued flavor overall but balanced. I liked it a lot

bottle, purchased 2 years ago and cellared since i heard the beer was super hot.  the amount of nuttiness in this beer was insane.  pistachio and rose, all over.  here are my notes: "plum hazy. minimal quickly dissipating head. alcohol from a mile away. cotton candy, malt, belgian esters, pretty wild aroma. tastes like alcohol, winey, cotton candy. dark rotten fruit, rose, and pistachio. so much rose and pistachio.  thick and syrupy.  kinda tastes like india.  i like it a decent amount.

draft at sheffields.  split this with nick yesterday.  he observed that it has zero smoked character.  i sensed a bit, but it was extremely remote, and i probably wouldnt have even thought of smoke if i didnt know that going in.  otherwise, the body and flavor were just like the 1 and 2.  that is, thick and smooth, plenty of chocolate, reasonably well balanced, and quite delicious.

i might be rating the wrong thing.  i thought i had the "king canmlat liquor.  but this is all i could find in the database.  "clear malt liquor. smells like sweet corn. tastes like pure corn syrup. my god"
hazy apricot color. incredibly complex. super pineapple and fruity. so summery, so appropriate. flavor is like a fruit smoothie. though upon bourbon suggestion it is there. very very sweet. awesome.

beer_brewer_name: Port Brewing Co / The Lost Abbey
review_blob: thanks nhorween.  im surprised ive never had it.  it was quite terrific.  poured murky ugly brown with a half inch of solid thick head.  nick probably shouldnt have poured out the yeast, but thats fine.  pretty much reminded me of a pretty hoppy barleywine.  id call it balanced.  plenty of malts and caramel, certainly.  i guess i dont have any specifics otherwise.  good stuff, alcohol well hidden
beer_name: Port Brewing Shark Attack Double Red Ale

review_blob: draft at maproom.  this was pretty crazy because i didnt get a deScription at first.   so i thought it smelled like fruit, chocolate, sweet, and alcohol, and i kinda wondered if it was a blend of 3 beers perhaps (in fact, i later saw that the maproom describes it as an american strong ale).  but theni saw on my phone that its listed as a mead here, and that made it make a lot more sense.  uber honeyed, uber sweet, a little bit of nuts and bourbon, perhaps.  still fruity.  really delicious.

thanks guerinfbfan. actually a little ugly. 2 inch thick head. slightly hazy rust brown.  pretty good, classic aroma.  lots of bananas and bread.  i mean, its basically a hefeweizen.  not sure why its listed as a wheat.  a bit of light fruity hops as well. surprisingly mild flavor.  most of the american hefeweizens ive had from good breweries have been boldly flavorful.  this is not the case here.  makes it more drinkable, perhaps.  has some flavor notes that remind me of a tripel.  somewhat thin, but very carbonated.  not a huge fan.
somewhat light for a porter in color. minimal head. smells like chocolate extract.  tastes a bit thin, but its pretty milky and chocolate.  really not bad.

no idea if im rating this right. the bottle says bluegrass brewing co. (BBC) amber ale... german style altbier.  there is no BBC amber ale, though except the amber waves.  so i assume its th altbier.  it pours a dark rust color.  with plentiful head. smells like malt extract. tastes like feet and the floor of a sauna where you place your feet.  theres a fair amount of water in it.  id say >99%.  nothing altiber about it.  its times like these when i think nick was right when he decided not to rate all the shit-fuck beers like this that have no distinct purpose.  well, i guess ill qualify that.  there is a purpose.  if the lay man in lexington goes to some bar and orders this, thats a victory for microbeer.  we cant expect everyone to jump to the levels of drinking/spending that we enjoy.  so kudos to that guy, and insofar as my example demonstrats, kudos to the beer.  but once that guy drinks more beer and grows a palate, fuck this beer.

cask at DotLA III. pretty sure i ranked this beer #1 in the voting, and i also think it was the first beer i had. BR cant do anything wrong, can they.  i had no idea there was that much alcohol in it. "light clear orange. well hopped, fruity, sweet aroma. super bitter. uber hoppy. zero malt, extremely dry"  guesss the numbers i assigneed to it that day dont correspond to a score better than some of the others i rated (but didnt score) that day.  oh well.

cask at DotLA III. haha, my friend got this and said it was just awful. so i took a tiny sip of his to try it.  wasnt intending on rating it, but that sip was so awful and unique that i can rate it easily based off that.  it was an awful, sawdust flavor. super hazy and ugly. super alcoholic. weird awful wood everywhere.  cedar, sure.  brian called it the worst beer ever, and he isnt super far off.
beer_name: Lakefront Bridge Burner Strong Ale - Oak Aged

review_blob: cask at DotLA III. i think this made my top 3 vote. maybe #2. "looks good. thick mustard head. super caramel nut aroma. flavor is a letdown. too sweet. awesome aroma though."  i liked it more as the festival went on and i realized how much most of the other stuff tasted the same thanks to the cask style.

cask at DotLA III. technically, this should have been the most interesting beer at the festival.  certainly the most rare.  which made this the biggest letdown by far.  "i think im over cask beer. dark brown, thin. smells of... brown ale? chocolate sorta, a bit nutty. sticky, sweet, thin"  this was totally uninteresting and pedestrian.

cask at DotLA III.  one member of our group mentioned Andes mints and thats pretty much spot on in terms of both flavor and aroma.  pretty extractish, but it wasn as horrible as the other ratings say.  and the body was appropriate.  dye it green?  how do you dye something that is black??
phlegm colored and hazy. i smell no saaz. not really a trippel either.  alcohol was pretty well hidden, but its weird how unlike the deScription this is.  spicy, and great.
beer_name: Rock Bottom Yorktown Sub Zero Winter Ale

review_blob: cask at DotLA III. not a lot to say about this. had it early in the fest as a response to the awful lakefront kriek. this was balanced, sweet, and great. probably one of the best krieks ive had. sweeter than most.
